'''Korea Taesong Bank''' ({{lang-ko|조선 대성 은행}};<ref name="Recent OFAC Actions - November 18, 2010 ">{{cite web | url=http://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/OFAC-Enforcement/Pages/20101118.aspx | title=Recent OFAC Actions - November 18, 2010 | publisher=US Treasury Department | accessdate=26 May 2015}}</ref> sometimes called '''Daesong Bank''', '''Dae-Sung Bank'''<ref name="How North Korea uses slaves to get around trade sanctions">{{cite web | url=http://www.businessinsider.com/how-north-korea-uses-slaves-to-get-around-trade-sanctions-2017-7 | title=How North Korea uses slaves to get around trade sanctions | publisher=Business Insider | date=11 July 2017 | accessdate=12 September 2017}}</ref> or '''Taesong General Trading Corporation''';<ref name="A Senior North Korean Banking Official Defects?">{{cite web | url=http://38north.org/2014/09/mmadden090314/ | title=A Senior North Korean Banking Official Defects? | publisher=38 North | date=3 September 2014 | accessdate=7 April 2016 | author=Madden, Michael}}</ref> in Japan called '''Chosun Tae Seong-Unhan'''; '''Tae-bank, Choson Taesong Unhaeng'''<ref name="コリア・デソン・バンク">{{cite web | url=http://www.meti.go.jp/press/2013/08/20130830001/20130830001-2.pdf | title=コリア・デソン・バンク | accessdate=26 May 2015 | language=Japanese}}</ref>) is a North Korean financial institution.<ref>[[Michael Breen (author)]] Kim Jong-Il, ''Revised and Updated: Kim Jong-il North Korea's Dear Leader'' 2012 1118153774 "Kim Jong-il: "the Daesong Group, which owns the Daesong Bank and the Vienna-based Golden Star Bank."</ref>
The Korea Taesong Bank is reportedly controlled by [[Room 39]].<ref name="Mapping North Korea Proliferation">{{cite web | url=http://www.cesim.fr/observatoire/eng/73/article/74 | title=Mapping North Korea Proliferation | publisher=THE NON-PROLIFERATION MONTHLY | work=cesim.fr | accessdate=26 May 2015 | author=Timothée Germain | pages=7 | issue=73}}</ref><ref name="How North Korea uses slaves to get around trade sanctions">{{cite web | url=http://www.businessinsider.com/how-north-korea-uses-slaves-to-get-around-trade-sanctions-2017-7 | title=How North Korea uses slaves to get around trade sanctions | publisher=Business Insider | date=11 July 2017 | accessdate=12 September 2017}}</ref>
The [[Golden Star Bank]], founded as a corporation in Vienna, Austria, was the only North Korean bank in Europe but was closed in 2004, was a subsidiary of the Taesong Bank.<ref name="Mapping North Korea Proliferation"/> [[Kwon Yong-nok]] was an auditor of the Golden Star Bank.<ref name="North Korean Policy Elites">{{cite web | url=http://www.dtic.mil/cgi-bin/GetTRDoc?AD=ADA427588 | title=North Korean Policy Elites; see footnote 66 | publisher=INSTITUTE FOR DEFENSE ANALYSES | date=June 2004 | accessdate=26 May 2015}}</ref>
"Taesong Bank, which received remittances from Mt. Kumgang tourism, is controlled by Room 39, and is also in charge of the exports of agricultural and fisheries products."<ref name="Room (Bureau) 38 allegedly restored">{{cite web | url=http://www.nkeconwatch.com/category/dprk-organizations/workers-party/central-committee/secretariat/bureau-39/page/2/ | title=Room (Bureau) 38 allegedly restored | publisher=North Korean Economic Watch | accessdate=26 May 2015}}</ref>
==Projects== * In 1989, it was to jointly develop the area around Mount Kumgang,<ref name="South, North Koreans Talk of Tourism Venture">{{cite web | url=http://articles.latimes.com/1989-02-02/business/fi-2672_1_north-korea | title=South, North Koreans Talk of Tourism Venture | publisher=Los Angeles Times | date=February 2, 1989 | accessdate=26 May 2015}}</ref> on the eastern coast of North Korea, as a tourist site with Hyundai.<ref name="THE TWO KOREAS AGREE TO DEVELOP RESORT IN NORTH">{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/02/02/world/the-two-koreas-agree-to-develop-resort-in-north.html | title=THE TWO KOREAS AGREE TO DEVELOP RESORT IN NORTH | publisher=New York Times | date=2 February 1989 | accessdate=26 May 2015 | author=SUSAN CHIRA}}</ref> * The company has been implicated in the smuggling of arms into and out of North Korea<ref name="Report of the Panel of Experts established pursuant to resolution 1874 (2009)">{{cite web | url=https://fas.org/nuke/guide/dprk/unsc-june2012.pdf | title=Report of the Panel of Experts established pursuant to resolution 1874 (2009) | publisher=United Nations, [[UN Security Council Sanctions Committee on North Korea|Security Council Sanctions Committee on North Korea]] | date=14 June 2012 | accessdate=26 May 2015}}</ref> and "Involved in facilitating proliferation financing projects."<ref name="Sanctions: UK Treasury part 29">{{cite web|url=http://www.bankinginsurancesecurities.com/sanctions_closures_fi_spam/Sanctions/uk_treasury_financial_sanctions_targets/sanctions_uk_treasury_part_29 |title=Sanctions: UK Treasury part 29; Sanctions in Action |publisher=UK Treasury |date=28 February 2011 |accessdate=26 May 2015 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
===Members=== * In 1989, Choe Su-gil, president of the Taesong Bank of North Korea<ref name="THE TWO KOREAS AGREE TO DEVELOP RESORT IN NORTH"/> and consultant to the Korean Association for the Promotion of Asian Trade.<ref name="South, North Koreans Talk of Tourism Venture"/> * In 2014, Kim Yo-jong took control of Taesong Bank, the [[Reunification and Development Bank]], and a number of tourism and railway projects<ref name="Kim appoints his younger sister to manage party coffers instead of slain uncle">{{cite web | url=http://sputniknews.com/voiceofrussia/news/2014_01_14/Kim-appoints-his-younger-sister-to-manage-party-coffers-instead-of-slain-uncle-5860/ | title=Kim appoints his younger sister to manage party coffers instead of slain uncle | publisher=Sputinik News | date=14 January 2014 | accessdate=26 May 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150527001317/http://sputniknews.com/voiceofrussia/news/2014_01_14/Kim-appoints-his-younger-sister-to-manage-party-coffers-instead-of-slain-uncle-5860/# | archive-date=2015-05-27 | dead-url=yes | df= }}</ref> * In 2014, Yun Tae-hyong, a regional manager in the Russian Far East for the Taesong Bank, defected to Russia.<ref name="A Senior North Korean Banking Official Defects?"/>
